From {{inh|en|enm|cherub}}, {{m|enm|cherube}}, {{m|enm|cherubin}}, {{m|enm|cherubine}}, {{m|enm|cherubym}}, {{m|enm|cherubyn}}, {{m|enm|cherybin}}, {{m|enm|gerubin}}, {{m|enm|jerubin|t=angel of the second highest order; depiction of such an angel}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=cherubin|pos=n|id=MED7474|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref> from {{inh|en|ang|cerubin}}, {{m|ang|cerubim}}, {{m|ang|ceruphin}}, {{m|ang|cherubin}}, from {{der|en|la|cherūbīn}}, {{m|la|cherūbīm}}, from {{der|en|grc|χερουβίν}}, {{m|grc|χερουβείν}}, {{m|grc|χερουβίμ}}, from {{der|en|he|כְּרוּבִים|tr=k'ruvím}}<ref name="OED">{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=31359|date=1889|nodot=yes}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref>; further {{unknown|en|etymology uncertain}}.

The English and Middle English word ''cherub''(''e'') is derived from {{der|en|la|cherub|t=cherub}} (the {{glossary|singular}} form of ''cherūbīm'', ''cherūbīn''), from {{der|en|grc|χερούβ}}, ultimately from {{der|en|he|כרוב|כְּרוּב|tr=kerúv}}. Because it was not always clear from Bible passages whether a single being or group of beings was being referred to, ''cherubin'' was used both as a singular word (plural {{m|en|cherubins}}) and plural word up to the 18th century. However, in Bible translations particularly from the 16th century onward ''cherub'' began to be favoured as the singular form, and from the 17th century ''cherubim'' as the plural form (influenced by {{cog|he|כְּרוּבִים|tr=k'ruvím}}).<ref name="OED"/>

The English word is cognate with {{cog|fr|chérubin}}, {{cog|it|cherubino}}, {{cog|osp|cherubin}} (modern {{cog|es|querubín}}), {{cog|gl|querubín}}, {{cog|pt|querubim}}.<ref name="OED"/>

